        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Huxley</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I congratulate you heartily on M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Huxley’s troubles being over.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is a horrid affair at the best of times; &amp; I fear a repitition will not make you feel younger.—</p>
<p>The Balanus is positively B. balanoides, &amp; you may positively state that the surface to which it adhered was not beneath level of lowest tide<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I will bring specimen when next I come to London.—</p>
<p>Ever yours | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is given by CD’s reference to the birth of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2484.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Noel Huxley</ref> (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2484.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Noel Huxley</ref> was born 31 December 1856 (L. Huxley ed. 1900, 1: 150–1).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD had described the tidal locations in which individuals of <hi rend="italic">Balanus balanoides</hi> were found in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>272.</note>
        </div>        
            
